 --- Erik Husby &lt;ehusby@...&gt; a �crit : &gt; I&#39;ve been following this
thread with some amusement that someone hasn&#39;t said
&gt; the obvious.
&gt; 
&gt; If you don&#39;t know how to test the method then you don&#39;t understand the
&gt; method.
&gt; 
&gt; For instance, if I know I am going to have a setter that simple sets a
&gt; variable and the
&gt; getter that returns it, then the method mentioned before of:
&gt; 
&gt; 	o.setThing( aThing );
&gt; 	assertEquals( aThing, o.getThing());
&gt; 
&gt; Works real well.
&gt; 
&gt; But If you have a more complex set/get combination such as a getter that
&gt; returns a clone 
&gt; of the variable then you would want something like:
&gt; 
&gt; 	Point p = new Point(99,99);
&gt; 	o.setPoint( p );
&gt; 	assert( &quot;Better not be same point object&quot;, p != o.getPoint());
&gt; 	assertEquals(&quot;But better have same x,y&quot;, p, o.getPoint());
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; As J. B. (Joe) Rainsberger said, &quot;do not test what cannot possibly break.&quot;
&gt; so you don&#39;t
&gt; really need to test the simple set/get combination. But by the same token,
&gt; make sure
&gt; that you really need the simple set/get combination. Don&#39;t add them simply
&gt; because you
&gt; think you might need them someday. Add them because a test you are writing
&gt; shows a need
&gt; for them.
&gt; 
